@OttoSuwenNFT @icebergy_ Yep, which is why I usually don't bother with them anymore. Just play with bluechips or buy on secondary if I think it has legs.

@icebergy_ To add on to this, they can be grinding multiple projects at once during an 8 hour work day. So if there are a few solid projects in a given week or two timespan, you're most likely coming out a winner.

@OttoSuwenNFT @icebergy_ From what I've noticed, great projects will allocate less than 10-15% to whitelists and have a public sale for the rest. When you over allocate, the floor just gets annihilated and people lose interest in the entire project quickly.

@icebergy_ If it's a big project, of course. Hiring 20 people for $8/hr for a week is ~9k. They each can handle 25-50 accounts each so assuming 36 accounts per person, thats 720 entries. You hit 5/720 on something like Asuna/Azuki and you've already made your money back. Absolutely crazy.
@OttoSuwenNFT @icebergy_ I hate the current WL meta. Auctions seem greedy sometimes but I think it's a lot easier to impose restrictions and add flexibility to them moreso than WLs.

@icebergy_ When whitelisting first started, a few friends and I paid fiverr people to grind them out on multiple accounts. Did the same for things like Mekaverse raffles.

It's just being done on a larger scale now that makes it all not worthwhile. Bring back gas wars or use 721A
